elements.2211.03263_23748202def4451314a987c94ab15: In recent years, multilingual pre-trained language models have gained prominence due to their remarkable performance on numerous downstream Natural Language Processing tasks (NLP)
elements.2211.03263_e197a2578a7af9f140b2d74e16cee: However, pre-training these large multilingual language models requires a lot of training data, which is not available for African Languages
elements.2211.03263_dfaa0d7b63130a190006b5c4f2e3b: Active learning is a semi-supervised learning algorithm, in which a model consistently and dynamically learns to identify the most beneficial samples to train itself on, in order to achieve better optimization and performance on downstream tasks
elements.2211.03263_200feacf37e30aa437bbd658cc891: Furthermore, active learning effectively and practically addresses real-world data scarcity
elements.2211.03263_d02c7795335cdeb3fd5b974a5d79b: Despite all its benefits, active learning, in the context of NLP and especially multilingual language models pretraining, has received little consideration
elements.2211.03263_d314c9f08d50a034436cac5e34bd2: , a multilingual language model pretrained from scratch on 23 African languages (the largest effort to date) using our novel self-active learning framework
elements.2211.03263_396f16ed1ac0b1cacf00045b157f1: Pretrained on a dataset significantly (14x) smaller than existing baselines,
elements.2211.03263_6d7a90cd303c5a46f5998c9507d35: outperforms many multilingual pretrained language models (AfriBERTa, XLMR-base, mBERT) on various NLP downstream tasks (NER, text classification, and sentiment analysis)
elements.2211.03263_f0259bf54a633ac0f0b3f0f4ff883: Additional out-of-domain sentiment analysis experiments show that
elements.2211.03263_223908c12540cd96e1efa9d768e2a: is able to generalize well across various domains
elements.2211.03263_c6c423f6fd19724ae34e045f3bdfb: We release the code source, and our datasets used in our framework at
elements.2211.03263_ad906491608af7cdf6ba5d0e89905: With the appearance of Transformer models
elements.2211.03263_237772f4d8817b64d05c63f0de123: , the field of Natural Language Processing (NLP) has seen the emergence of powerful multilingual pre-trained language models (MPLMs), such as mBERT
elements.2211.03263_f69ce5855e815836ec96bc0cbfd81: These prominent models have helped achieve state-of-the-art (SOTA) performance in many downstream NLP tasks such as named entity recognition (NER)
elements.2211.03263_b90cb0878b85da6bd6956b4cf5965: However they usually require a large amount of unlabeled text corpora for good performance: mBERT was trained on Wikipedia (2,500M words) and BookCorpus
elements.2211.03263_1e05320ec443932d43e2d04c21d88: (800M words) across 104 languages - 5 of which are African; mT5 supports 101 languages (13 African) and XLM-R supports 100 languages (8 African), and were trained on mC4
elements.2211.03263_3067969b1fd07af21ec7b133ae0fb: This requirement for large-scale datasets contrasts sharply with the scarcity of available text corpora for African languages, which has pushed them into low-resource settings and largely excluded them from the pre-training phase of these large pre-trained models
elements.2211.03263_617b7bb69ee61e55899bdde2c8d46: This exclusion, leads very often, to a poor performance on languages unseen during pre-training
elements.2211.03263_dc4d1ae68238ada0042efe29d5d79: which eventually leads to inability to carry out the required NLP task.
